The above and other objects, features and advantages of the invention will become apparent from a consideration of the following detailed description presented in connection with the accompanying drawings in which:


FIG. 1A shows a side view of a person riding a motorcycle having a foot board and a foot brake made in accordance with the teachings of the prior art;


FIGS. 1B through 1D show close-up side views of the foot board and the lever arm and pedal of the prior art foot brake shown in FIG. 1A as the foot of a rider shows the different movements necessary to actuate the brake when the foot begins in the position shown in FIG. 1A;


FIG. 1E shows a top view of the prior art foot brake lever assembly shown in FIGS. 1A through 1D, along with a conventional foot board;


FIG. 1F shows a top view of another embodiment of a prior art foot brake lever assembly similar to that shown in FIGS. 1A through 1D, but with a different actuator mechanism.


FIG. 2 shows a top, partially cut away view of a foot brake lever assembly for use with motorcycles disposed adjacent a conventional foot board in accordance with the principles of the present invention;


FIG. 3 shows a side-view of the brake lever assembly shown in FIG. 2;


FIGS. 4A through 4C show close-up side views of the brake lever assembly used on a motorcycle having foot boards in accordance with the principles of the present invention as the foot of the rider moves through the necessary movements to actuate the brake;


FIG. 5 shows a perspective view of the brake lever assembly of FIGS. 2 and 3 with a brake pad attached in accordance with the principles of the present invention;


FIG. 6 shows a perspective view of a brake lever assembly similar to that shown in FIG. 5, but with a modification made to the brake pad support.


FIG. 7 shows a cross-sectional view of the brake pad support with a brake pad disposed thereon in accordance with the principles of the present invention;


FIG. 7A shows a top view of a brake pad made in accordance with the principles of the present invention;


FIG. 8 shows a side view of an alternate embodiment of the present invention, wherein the angle of the actuator arm is modified;


FIG. 9 shows a perspective view of an alternate embodiment of the present invention which utilizes an actuator mechanism similar to that shown in FIG. 1F, but which is modified to achieve the advantages of the present invention; and


FIG. 10 shows a side view of the embodiment of the invention shown in FIG. 9.
